in multilevel inheritance in java we use **super** keyword.

I have made a small example so you understand the flow of execution of a super constructor when used in inheritance.

    ***Calling Default Super Constructor***

        class A {
    
    	public int a ;
    	public int aa ;
    	A(){
    	   this.a = 20 ;
    		System.out.println(&quot;Constructor of class A is called&quot;) ;
    	
    	}
    	A(int aa){
    	
    		this.aa = aa ;
    		System.out.println(&quot;Parameterized Constructor of class A is called&quot;) ;
    	}
    	
    	
    
    }
    
    class B extends A{
    
    	public int b ;
    	public int bb ;
    	B(){
    	this.b = 20 ;
    		System.out.println(&quot;Constructor of class B is called&quot;) ;
    	}
    	B(int bb){
    	
    		this.bb = bb ;
    		System.out.println(&quot;Parameterized Constructor of class B is called&quot;) ;
    	}
    
    }
    
    class C extends B{
    
    	public int c ;
    	public int cc ;
    	C(){
    		this.c = 30 ;
    		System.out.println(&quot;Constructor of class C is called&quot;) ;
    	
    	}
    	
    	C(int cc){
    	
    		this.cc = cc ;
    		System.out.println(&quot;Parameterized Constructor of class C is called&quot;) ;
    	}
    
    
    }
    
    class MultiLevel{
    
    	public static void main(String args[]){
    	
    		new C() ;
    	
    	}
    
    }

